messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Here is the analysis based strictly on the provided code.

What is the base prefix for client routes?
- All client routes are mounted under /clients in index.js via app.use('/clients', clientRoutes).

Full HTTP request paths and their supported methods (as implemented by the code)

1) Path: /clients
- Implemented methods:
  - GET /clients => getClients
  - POST /clients => createClient
- Path with parameters:
  - None (no path parameters)
  - Note: You can pass ?page=... as a query parameter for pagination (req.query.page)
- HEAD: Acceptable? Yes, because there are GET handlers for /clients. Express will respond to HEAD requests using the same handling as GET for this route.
- OPTIONS: Acceptable? No (no explicit OPTIONS handler or middleware for this route)
- TRACE: Acceptable? No (no TRACE handler)
- GET: Acceptable? Yes (GET is defined)
- POST: Acceptable? Yes (POST is defined)
- PUT: Acceptable? No (no PUT handler on /clients)
- PATCH: Acceptable? No (no PATCH handler on /clients)
- DELETE: Acceptable? No (no DELETE handler on /clients)
- Explanation: The router defines GET('/') and POST('/') for this path, mounted at /clients.

2) Path: /clients/user
- Implemented methods:
  - GET /clients/user => getClientsByUser
- Path with parameters:
  - None (no path parameters)
  - Query parameters may be used (req.query) for filtering; the function uses searchQuery from query
- HEAD: Acceptable? Yes, because there is a GET handler for this path; HEAD will be handled similarly by Express.
- OPTIONS: Acceptable? No (no explicit OPTIONS handler)
- TRACE: Acceptable? No
- GET: Acceptable? Yes
- POST: Acceptable? No
- PUT: Acceptable? No
- PATCH: Acceptable? No
- DELETE: Acceptable? No
- Explanation: The route is defined as router.get('/user', getClientsByUser) under /clients, so GET is available for this exact path.

3) Path: /clients/{id}
- Implemented methods:
  - PATCH /clients/:id => updateClient
  - DELETE /clients/:id => deleteClient
- Path parameters:
  - { id } is used in the route (/:id)
- HEAD: Acceptable? No for this path because there is no GET handler defined for /clients/:id in the routes (only PATCH and DELETE exist). HEAD would typically be tied to GET, which is not present here.
- OPTIONS: Acceptable? No (no explicit OPTIONS handler)
- TRACE: Acceptable? No
- GET: Acceptable? No (no GET for /clients/:id)
- POST: Acceptable? No
- PUT: Acceptable? No
- PATCH: Acceptable? Yes
- DELETE: Acceptable? Yes
- Explanation: The route defines PATCH and DELETE for /clients/:id, with the path parameter {id}.

Summary of method acceptance (based on the code)
- All methods: False (the code does not implement every HTTP method for a single endpoint)
- HEAD: Partially acceptable
  - Acceptable for /clients and /clients/user (due to existing GET handlers)
  - Not applicable for /clients/{id} (no GET handler for that path)
- GET: Acceptable (for /clients and /clients/user)
- POST: Acceptable (for /clients)
- PUT: Not acceptable (no PUT handlers)
- PATCH: Acceptable (for /clients/{id})
- DELETE: Acceptable (for /clients/{id})
- OPTIONS: Not acceptable (no OPTIONS handlers for these routes)
- TRACE: Not acceptable (no TRACE handlers)

Explanation tying it together
- The endpoints are defined in routes/clients.js and mounted under /clients in index.js.
- GET routes exist for /clients and /clients/user, so GET is allowed for those paths; HEAD is effectively allowed for those routes because Express handles HEAD automatically when a GET route exists.
- The only endpoints that exist for manipulating a specific client by id are PATCH and DELETE on /clients/{id}; there is no GET, PUT, or other methods for that path, so those methods are not acceptable there.
- There are no explicit OPTIONS, TRACE, or PUT routes defined for any of these paths, so those methods are not acceptable for the implemented endpoints.
